<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-566-236  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 566 236.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  August 21 1989 v10 n33 p34(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>World's smallest lasers aimed at computing, telecom apps: to beused with fiber optics.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Coursey, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Microscopic lasers may be used to increase computing speed.andP;  Asmicroprocessors get smaller and faster, the time it takeselectrons to flow across wires between chips has become a majorfactor limiting speed increases.andP;  Information can move much morequickly across optical fiber than through wires.andP;  A new technologyfrom Bell Communications Research and AT and T Bell Laboratoriespacks 2 million lasers onto a half-inch-square chip.andP;  Short-termapplications for the micro-lasers are expected to includefiber-optic communications and high-speed computers.andP;  Because thelasers operate at a 1-milliamp current, they can be run at normalmicroprocessor power levels.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Future TechnologiesLasersMiniaturizationFuture of ComputingPerformance ImprovementProcessor SpeedFiber Optics.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>